  <H1>PROF.JEYLAN WOLYIE</H1>  
  <P><STRong><EM>HARAMAYA UNIVERSITY PROFESSOR</strong></EM></P>
  <P><em>I am a professor at Haramaya University. My research focuses on the intersection of <strong>ethinic identity, conflict, and educational practice,</strong> with emphases on: How <strong>resource politics and social institutions</strong> shape inte-ethinic conflict, The <strong>discursive and identity processes</strong> that mobilize communities toward violence or peace, The role of <strong>language and education policy</strong> as mechanism of power and emancipayion in multi-ethnic settings, strategies for <strong>critical peace education</strong> and transformative pedagogy in post-conflict and rural contexts.</em> </P>
   <a href="CONTACT-ME.HTML">Contact Information</a>
  <hr>
  <h3>Background & Education</h3>
  <ul>
  <li>Born on 16 July 1970 in rural village in Bale-Robe, Oromia. Attended Galama primary school, Robe secondary school, then Addis Ababa university.</li>
  <li>Earned MA in social science for critical educators from <strong><a href="https://www.umu.se/en/">UMEA University, Sweden.</a></strong></li>
  <li>Completed my PhD in peace and conflict resolution at <a href="https://www.haramaya.edu.et/"> Haramaya University</a> in 2016; dissertation analyzed intercommunity conflicts at the oromo-somali border.</li>
  <li>Awarded full professorship in cultural and social analysis by Haramaya University's administrative board in April 2018.</li>
</ul>
  <hr>
  <h3>Academic & Professional contributions</h3>
  <ul>
  <li>Associate professor in the college of social sciences and humanities at Haramaya, with reseaarch focusing on identity, inter-ethinic conflict, land disputes, peace education, and youth livehoods in fragile rural settings</li>
  <li>My publicatons has appeared in journals such as international area studies review, African identities, Ethinic studies review, and One health outlook</li>
  <li>Notable works includes topics like peace-building education, conflict sensitivity through mindfulness, youth aspirations in agriculture, and land-related conflict in Ethiopia</li>
</ul>
  <hr>
  <h3>Leadership & service</h3>
  <ul>
  <li>I have supervised and examined more than 100 Mater's students and served as external examiner for PhD canidates in Ethiopia and South Africa.</li>
  <li>Key leadership roles at <a href="https://www.haramaya.edu.et/">Haramaya University</a>: Head of public relations, Dean of the college of social sciences and humanities,committe member on institutional legislation and process reengineering, and served as vice president for administration and student affairs at Haramaya University in Ethiopia. </li>
</ul>
